      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":339,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed, let your body ease into the effort. Conversational pace throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable easy pace. You should be able to hold a full conversation. This is aerobic base building — resist the urge to push.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gradually slow to a walk. Take 5 minutes to stretch calves, hip flexors, and hamstrings.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5 minutes of brisk walking or very light jogging before easing into your easy pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 2-3 minutes, then do light dynamic stretching focusing on hips and legs.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This Monday run sets the aerobic tone for the week. At your VDOT of 49.7, easy runs are the foundation of your marathon fitness — they build mitochondrial density, improve fat oxidation, and support recovery from harder efforts. Keep the pace honest: 5:07–5:39/km. If it feels too easy, that's exactly right. Your 3:15 marathon goal is built on the quality of these aerobic miles, not just the hard sessions.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Marathon Pace Progression Run\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":62,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":271,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy conversational pace for the first 3 km. Let your legs loosen up fully before asking anything of them.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into marathon goal pace — 4:31/km. This should feel controlled and purposeful, not labored. Think 'comfortably hard.' You're teaching your body what race day feels like.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Return to easy pace for the final 3 km. Let your heart rate come down naturally. Notice how your body responds after sustained marathon effort.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy warm-up jog. Include 4 x 20-second strides at the end of the warm-up to prime your legs for marathon pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3 km easy cool-down jog followed by 5 minutes of static stretching — focus on quads, hamstrings, and calves.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is one of the most important workouts in your marathon build. Running at your goal marathon pace (4:31/km) trains your body to run economically at race effort — improving lactate clearance, running economy, and mental familiarity with the pace. At 7 km of marathon pace work, this is a moderate stimulus. Over the coming weeks, we'll extend this segment progressively. The key is consistency: hit the pace, don't exceed it, and finish feeling like you had more to give.\",\"perceived_effort\":6},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":65,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":237,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy 3 km jog. Include 4 x 20-second accelerations in the final 5 minutes to prepare your neuromuscular system for fast running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":237,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 1000m at interval pace (3:57/km). Each rep should feel hard but controlled — you should be able to finish each one. Take 90 seconds of easy jogging between reps. If you're dying on rep 3, slow down slightly rather than stopping.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"90 seconds easy jog between each interval. Keep moving — don't stop completely. This active recovery helps clear lactate and prepares you for the next rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy 3 km cool-down jog. This is non-negotiable — it accelerates recovery and helps your body process the training stimulus.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy warm-up jog with 4 x 20-second strides at the end. Do not skip the warm-up before intervals — cold muscles and fast running are a poor combination.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3 km easy cool-down jog. Follow with 10 minutes of gentle stretching and consider a short foam roll session if available.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2Max intervals are the sharpest tool in your marathon toolkit. Running at 3:57/km raises your aerobic ceiling — improving your maximal oxygen uptake and making marathon pace feel more sustainable. Five 1000m reps is a solid but manageable dose at this stage of your build. The 90-second recovery is intentional: long enough to let you run the next rep well, short enough to keep the aerobic demand high. These sessions are hard — that's the point. But hard should mean focused and controlled, not desperate. If a rep goes off the rails, it's more useful to slow down than to blow up.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Aerobic Run with Marathon Pace Finish\",\"target_distance_km\":26,\"target_duration_minutes\":135,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":271,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 2 km very easy — slower end of your easy range (5:39/km). Let your body wake up and find its rhythm.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":95,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable easy pace (5:07–5:39/km) for the bulk of the run. Stay aerobic, stay relaxed. Fuel at 45 and 90 minutes — practice your race day nutrition strategy.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 4–5 km at marathon goal pace (4:31/km). This is the key stimulus: running at race pace on tired legs. It should feel hard but achievable. This is where marathon fitness is built.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk or very easy jog for the final 5–10 minutes. Begin your recovery routine immediately after finishing.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start conservatively — the first 2 km should feel almost too easy. You have 26 km ahead of you. There's no benefit to starting fast.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes immediately after finishing. Prioritize rehydration and carbohydrate intake within 30 minutes. Gentle stretching after that.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the cornerstone of marathon training. At 26 km, you're already at a strong base. The marathon-pace finish (last 4–5 km at 4:31/km) is a deliberate training stimulus — it teaches your body to run efficiently when fatigued, which is exactly what the final 10 km of a marathon demands. This is also your opportunity to practice race day nutrition: take in carbohydrates at 45 and 90 minutes, experiment with what works for your stomach, and treat this as a dress rehearsal. Keep the easy portions genuinely easy — the value of the long run comes from time on feet and the quality finish, not from grinding the middle miles.\",\"perceived_effort\":7}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
